From: Percival <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 14 May 2026 01:05:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] wifi: ath12k: tolerate overlapping channels when merging
 wideband multi-pdev bands

ath12k_mac_update_band() exists to support the "split mac" topology - two
MACs in the same band advertising disjoint channel ranges that get merged
into one supported_band. The function WARNs and refuses if the second MAC
re-enables a channel that the first already enabled.

On QCN9274 dualmac boards (single chip, two wideband PHYs each capable of
5 GHz + 6 GHz), firmware reports overlapping channel lists for both PHYs.
The split-mac assumption doesn't hold: both pdevs claim the full 5 GHz set
and (when applicable) the full 6 GHz set. mac_register then fails with:

  WARN at ath12k/mac.c:13149  ath12k_mac_update_band
  ath12k_mac_register failed
  ath12k_core_qmi_firmware_ready failed
  ath12k_pci ...: unable to start hw group

Without proper merging support for this topology yet, at least let
mac_register complete by treating already-enabled channels in the merge
target as a no-op. The first pdev "owns" the band; the second one's
redundant channels are silently dropped. The device probes and wlan
interfaces appear, which is strictly better than bailing out entirely.

Tested-on: QCN9274 hw2.0 PCI (GL.iNet Flint 3) with WLAN.WBE.1.6 fw.

Signed-off-by: Percival <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c
+++ b/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/mac.c
@@ -13144,12 +13144,19 @@ static int ath12k_mac_update_band(struct
 	for (i = 0; i < new_band->n_channels; i++) {
 		if (new_band->channels[i].flags & IEEE80211_CHAN_DISABLED)
 			continue;
-		/* An enabled channel in new_band should not be already enabled
-		 * in the orig_band
+		/*
+		 * In the split-mac topology a channel enabled by the new pdev
+		 * is expected to still be disabled in the orig band. On wideband
+		 * QCN9274 dualmac, however, firmware reports the *same* channel
+		 * range from both PHYs; the second pdev's claim on an already
+		 * enabled channel is a no-op rather than an error.
 		 */
-		if (WARN_ON(!(orig_band->channels[i].flags &
-			      IEEE80211_CHAN_DISABLED)))
-			return -EINVAL;
+		if (!(orig_band->channels[i].flags & IEEE80211_CHAN_DISABLED)) {
+			ath12k_dbg(ar->ab, ATH12K_DBG_MAC,
+				   "mac band %d ch %d already owned by earlier pdev, skipping\n",
+				   orig_band->band, new_band->channels[i].hw_value);
+			continue;
+		}
 		orig_band->channels[i].flags &= ~IEEE80211_CHAN_DISABLED;
 	}
 	return 0;
